ty score for each bin based on the item and the bins array. Each function must be a vectorized numpy function, using the allowed operations without any loops or conditionals. I'll think of different mathematical operations and combinations to create unique priority calculations.\n\nLet me start by understanding the problem. The function 'priority' takes an item and an array of bins. It needs to return an array where each element is a priority score for each bin. The goal is to find a heuristic that optimizes the bin packing problem.\n\nI'll consider various mathematical approaches to compute the priority. Maybe using ratios, differences, logarithms, exponentials, trigonometric functions, etc. Each function should combine these operations in a unique way.\n\nI should also ensure that the functions handle edge cases, such as when bins contain NaNs or Infs, and when the item is very large or very small. Since the function is vectorized, all operations should work element-wise without any loops.\n\nLet me think of some unique combinations:\n\n1. Using the difference between the item and each bin, then applying exponential and logarithmic functions.\n2. Combining ratios of item to bin with sine functions.\n3. Using the sum of item and bin, then applying log transformations.\n4. Maybe adding or subtracting different terms to create a unique priority score.\n\nI'll try to create 10 distinct functions by varying the operations and their combinations. Each function will use a different arrangement of allowed operations to ensure uniqueness.\n\nNow, I'll proceed to draft each function, ensuring that each one is unique in its operation combination.\n</think>\n\nHere are 10 unique implementations of the `priority` function, each using a distinct combination of allowed operations to compute the priority scores for each bin:\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item - bins) * np.exp(item + bins) + np.log(bins + 1)\n```\n\n```python