d be the same for all bins, which isn't correct. Wait, no, because for each bin, remaining is 1 - bins[i], so each bin has a different remaining.\n\nSo, the priority for each bin is exp((1 - bins[i]) - item).\n\nBut this may not capture the best fit; perhaps we want to prioritize bins where the remaining space is as close as possible to the item.\n\nAnother approach: the priority could be the absolute difference between the remaining space and the item, but we want to minimize this difference. So, lower difference means higher priority.\n\nBut since we want higher priority where the difference is smaller, perhaps we can compute 1/(1 + difference), so that smaller differences give higher priority.\n\nBut using allowed operations, perhaps we can compute the difference as (remaining - item), but we want to prioritize where this is as close to zero as possible.\n\nAlternatively, we can compute the difference squared, but that's not in the allowed operations. Wait, allowed operations include subtract, multiply, etc., but not square directly. But we can compute (remaining - item)^2 using multiply: (remaining - item) * (remaining - item).\n\nSo, function 2:\n\npriority = (remaining - item) ** 2\n\nBut since we can't use exponentiation directly, we can compute it as multiply:\n\npriority = np.multiply(remaining - item, remaining - item)\n\nBut in numpy, we can just do (remaining - item)**2.\n\nBut in the function, we can write:\n\nreturn np.square(remaining - item)\n\nBut that's another allowed function, np.square.\n\nWait, but in the allowed operations, I don't see square. The allowed operations are sqrt, exp, log, sin, cos, tan, norm, std, mean, var, max, min, add, subtract, multiply, divide, log10, log2, log1p.\n\nSo, square isn't directly allowed, but we can compute it using multiply.\n\nSo, function 2:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = 1 - bins\n    diff = remaining - item\n    return np.exp(-np.abs(diff))  # Higher priority