unctions should not modify the bins array.\n- The functions should not use any loops or conditionals if they can be avoided, but they are allowed.\n- The functions must return a numpy array of the same size as bins.\n\n### Final Notes:\n- Ensure that each function is unique in its mathematical expression.\n- Each function must compute a valid priority score for each bin.\n- The functions should be as diverse as possible in their implementation.\n\n### Deliverables:\n- 10 unique functions, each implementing a different heuristic.\n\n### Instructions for Writing Functions:\n- Use the allowed operations to create unique mathematical expressions.\n- Ensure that the functions are valid and can be run without errors.\n- Each function must return a numpy array of the same shape as bins.\n\n### Example of a Valid Function:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Invalid Examples:\n- Functions that modify the bins array.\n- Functions that use forbidden operations or syntax.\n- Functions that do not return a numpy array of the same size as bins.\n- Functions that are not valid Python code.\n\n### Additional Considerations:\n- The priority function is part of a heuristic, so it should not be too computationally expensive.\n- The functions should be as efficient as possible, given the allowed operations.\n\n### Conclusion:\nThe goal is to generate 10 unique and valid priority functions that can be used in a bin-packing heuristic to select the best bin for each item based on the computed priority scores.\n</think>\n\n### Implementation 1:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 2:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + bins) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 3:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * bins) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 4:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.sqrt(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 5:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log(bins + 1e-10)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 6:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.max(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 7:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.min(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 8:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 9:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sinh(np.pi * (item / bins))\n", 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.median(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.tan(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log(np.mean(bins) + 1)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * (np.mean(bins) ** 2)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log(bins + 1)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * (np.mean(bins) ** 3)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'de