perhaps function 10 can be:\n\nnp.where(item > bins, (item - bins) * log10(bins + 1), (bins - item) * sin(pi * item / bins)).\n\nBut that's getting a bit complex. Let me see.\n\nWait, but each function needs to return an array of the same size as bins, computed based on the item and bins.\n\nI think I can proceed by creating 10 different mathematical expressions, each using a unique combination of operations.\n\nLet me list out 10 different ideas:\n\n1. Use log2 of (item + bins) multiplied by exp(item - bins).\n2. Use (item * (bins + 1)) multiplied by sin(pi * item / bins).\n3. Use sinh(item) multiplied by cos(bins).\n4. Use (item / (bins + 1)) multiplied by tan(pi * (item / bins)).\n5. Use (item + bins) multiplied by exp(item - bins) plus sin(pi * (item / bins)).\n6. Use tanh(item - bins) multiplied by (item + bins).\n7. Use (item^2 + bins) multiplied by log2(item^2 + bins).\n8. Use (item * bins) multiplied by sin(2*pi*item / bins).\n9. Use sinh(item / (bins + 1)) multiplied by cosh(item).\n10. Use max(item - bins, 0) multiplied by min(item + bins, 1).\n\nWait, but some of these might not be valid or could cause division by zero. For example, in function 4, if bins are zero, division by zero occurs. So I need to handle that.\n\nAlternatively, in function 4, I can use np.maximum(bins, 1e-8) to avoid division by zero.\n\nSimilarly, in function 9, item / (bins + 1) could be problematic if bins are -1, but since bins are from bin packing, they are likely positive.\n\nWait, bins are the capacities of the bins. So they are positive floats. So division by bins is safe.\n\nWait, but in the function, bins can be zero? Or are they positive? Since it's a bin packing problem, bins are likely to have positive capacities. So perhaps no division by zero unless bins are zero, which is unlikely.\n\nBut to be safe, perhaps I can add a small epsilon to avoid division by zero.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps in some functions, I can use np.maximum(bins, 1e-8) to prevent division by zero.\n\nBut for the sake of time, perhaps I can proceed without handling that, assuming bins are positive.\n\nNow, let me structure each function.\n\nFunction 1:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log2(bins + 1)) * np.exp(item - bins)\n\nFunction 2:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * (bins + 1)) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\nFunction 3:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.sinh(item) * np.cos(bins)\n\nFunction 4:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item / (bins + 1)) * np.tan(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\nFunction 5:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + bins) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\nFunction 6:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.tanh(item - bins) * (item + bins)\n\nFunction 7:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item**2 + bins) * np.log2(item**2 + bins)\n\nFunction 8:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * bins) * np.sin(2 * np.pi * (item / bins))\n\nFunction 9:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.sinh(item / (bins + 1)) * np.cosh(item)\n\nFunction 10:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.max(item - bins, 0) * np.min(item + bins, 1)\n\nWait, but np.max and np.min here are applied element-wise. So for each bin, compute max(item - bins[i], 0) multiplied by min(item + bins[i], 1). Wait, but min(item + bins[i], 1) might not be necessary. Alternatively, perhaps just max and min with 0 and 1.\n\nAlternatively, function 10 could be:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.where(item > bins, (item - bins) * np.log2(bins + 1), (bins - item) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)))\n\nBut this is more c